>> Especially the part where it is written that the "1.n*" values are not recommended.
> 
> We don't recommend the "1.n*" notation, because it means that your app shouldn't run in a newer version of Java.
> 
> In the case where there is only one version available on the system, like in Mac OS X 10.6, we have to effectively ignore 1.4* and 1.5* requests - because from an end-user's perspective, it's better to attempt the launch and possibly fail than to not launch at all and not even get the possibility of succeeding.
> 
> Besides some corner cases, there really is no benefit to using "1.n*" instead of "1.n+". We even print a warning to the console if we have to ignore the "1.n*" directive.
> 
> The "1.n*" notation is actually more helpful in Java Web Start applications that can specify multiple resource blocks and load different resources depending on the version - I think it's usefulness for double-clickable applications though is limited, given the current launching logic and plist structure.
